description.narrative: Key Result Area 3.1.5: Children in humanitarian situations have increased protection, particularly from floods, landmine/ERW and during forced repatriations from bordering countries, which contributes to Access To Justice, Children With Disabilities, Equitable Access To Quality Education, Harmful Practices (Fgm/C And Child Marriage), Other Cross-Sectoral Programme Areas, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children (Covid), Private Sector Engagement, Skills Development, Social Protection. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, girls and boys including adolescents, living with families and outside of family care are increasingly free from violence and exploitation and from the threat of violence and exploitation in their homes, schools and communities and in institutions, including during humanitarian situations.

description.narrative: Child protection services were strengthened to also respond to the COVID-19 emergency, with more than 14,000 children at risk of or experiencing harm and unnecessary family separation benefiting from direct services. UNICEF actively engaged in ‘preparedness and response' activities in the context of COVID-19, focusing on protecting children in alternative care, adapting case management practices and deploying additional social workers in all 25 provinces. A key step forward was the launch of Primero, a digital case management tool, interoperable with NGOs, improving collaboration and referrals as well as representing a backbone of a nationwide child protection practice | Status:On-track | As-of Date:21/08/2020
